reviews.review_text: Don't be fooled by the lack of reviews this is great. have only heard the first few so far but seems to be jerry playing around on an acoustic working on the arrangements for the tunes to be on workingmans.  the sound is great for what it is, feels like he's sitting on a stool right there next to my desk.
nice voice Casey Jones exhibits a nice singing style by Jerry Garcia.
Miss ya Jerry So nice to hear this comfotrtable laid back Jerry

GREAT FIND Superb listen, like Jerry's in the room with you, and hard to "find" due to the date.
Peace, Bob
Five Million Stars For me, who loves Jerry's music, this is priceless.  Thank you.
Wonderful What a great listen. W.D. taking form. I could listen to Casey Jones all night!

Surely from 1969 rather than 1970 Engaging snapshot of the creative process.  I would have made it a 5 star rating but for SQ and completeness, but my rating should be understood as reflecting its archaeological value rather than sound/performance quality.  

Regarding the date, nearly all the tunes in this collection would be played by the full band starting midway through 1969, some of them haven't yet attained the form here they would have when they first hit the stage. (Though Dire Wolf sounds very much like the first live performance on 6-7-69, Garcia on acoustic guitar, and Casey Jones has the same steady beat as some of the first performances.)

This has to be from May or June of 69.

There's no way songs they had been playing for 6 months or so would sound this rough in early 1970 when they were rehearsing for Workingman's Dead.
A Grateful discovery .     I asked my phone for " assorted Grateful Dead acoustic " and some incredible archive.org Jerry just popped outta the garden and rabbit hole !   Lovin' it !
